The Delta State coordinator for the State Employment and Expenditure for Results (SEEFOR), Mr Frank Akopkwu, has revealed that the World Bank and European Union have allocated $58.8 million to Delta State for the implementation of SEEFOR project in the state, in the last five years. Akpokwu, who disclosed this in Asaba yesterday while briefing journalists on the implementation activities of the state SEEFOR, noted that the programme was designed to run for five years, saying the project effectively kick off its implementation in the state in 2013 and billed to end by September, 2020. He said, “SEEFOR is a World Bank/European Union intervention partnership programme  with states, introduced through the Federal Government of Nigeria. It is currently being implemented as a pilot phase in four states, Delta, Edo, Bayelsa and Rivers. “The total fund allocation to Delta SEEFOR projects is $58.8 million, comprising the International Development Association (IDA), Credit of $41.1 million and European Union (EU) grant of $17.7 million, which is complemented with an annual Government Counterpart Cash Contribution (GCCC).” He said since inception of SEEFOR in the state, over 262 roads maintenance were awarded, which provided direct employment for over 9,515 jobs for youths and constructed 12.7km of roads among others. In his remarks, the National Coordinator, SEEFOR, Dr. Grag Onu said that Delta state surpassed the component A of the programme. He said at the National level, database of all of the roads constructed by SEEFOR had been captured for onward transmission to the World Bank.